    <node id="PDF">
      <data key="d0">PDF</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">PDF refers to the Portable Document Format, serving as the digital file format utilized for the report document within the Open Compute Project (OCP) Composable Memory Systems (CMS) sub-project. Specified in the document metadata as a standardized, platform-independent container, this format ensures consistent rendering and layout integrity across diverse systems. It acts as the definitive archival container for the technical update report, with multiple distinct file instances existing within this entity classification. These instances reflect a versioned document lifecycle characterized by content revisions, embedded media, and varying compression levels.

Documented file sizes for these PDF instances range widely from 0.13 MB to 38.01 MB. Specific recorded sizes include 0.13 MB, 0.26 MB, 0.65 MB, 0.75 MB, 0.88 MB, 0.94 MB, 1.15 MB, 1.18 MB, 1.20 MB, 1.24 MB, 1.33 MB, 1.38 MB, 1.43 MB, 1.45 MB, 1.56 MB, 1.72 MB, 1.77 MB, 1.80 MB, 1.92 MB, 1.99 MB, 2.04 MB, 2.34 MB, 2.53 MB, 2.69 MB, 2.75 MB, 2.92 MB, 2.94 MB, 3.46 MB, 3.69 MB, 3.76 MB, 4.35 MB, 4.57 MB, and 38.01 MB. Additionally, one specific record identifies a file size of 3.66 MB. Notable instances include the "7525 Report" and files identified as vectorized, with specific descriptions highlighting instances of 0.94 MB, 1.56 MB, and 2.69 MB.

Ingestion timestamps indicate coordinated batch processing, with the majority of events occurring on 2026-03-07 between 19:05:19 and 19:05:23. Specific timestamps recorded include 19:05:19, 19:05:20, 19:05:21, 19:05:22, and 19:05:23. However, a discrepancy exists regarding the ingestion date, as one record specifies an ingestion on 2026-03-08 at 18:48:42. This variation suggests either a subsequent update cycle or distinct archival batches beyond the initial cluster. Collectively, these attributes affirm PDF's role as the stable, interoperable, and officially designated format for the OCP CMS technical documentation.&lt;SEP&gt;File format of the report document.&lt;SEP&gt;File format of the report.&lt;SEP&gt;The file format of the document.&lt;SEP&gt;PDF is the file format of the document.</data>
