    <node id="Core Report">
      <data key="d0">Core Report</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Core Report is a classification used within a research library—specifically the server architecture research repository—to denote high-priority, strategically important technical documentation. The tag “core” signifies central relevance and foundational significance, particularly with respect to server architecture development and foundational system components. This classification reflects both operational urgency and conceptual centrality: it is applied to reports deemed essential for guiding research direction, informing architectural decisions, and supporting critical infrastructure design. The tag appears consistently across multiple descriptions as “core”, “priority: core”, or its bilingual equivalent “优先级/核心”, reinforcing its standardized usage as a priority marker rather than a unique document title. All references situate the Core Report exclusively within the context of server architecture research, with no indication of application to other domains or repositories. The term functions as a metadata label—indicating importance, strategic value, and thematic centrality—rather than naming a specific, singular report; thus, “Core Report” refers collectively to a class of high-importance documentation within this specialized research ecosystem.&lt;SEP&gt;The Mt. Diablo Server Scope is classified as a core report, signifying high priority and relevance within the research library.</data>
