    <node id="Core">
      <data key="d0">Core</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Core represents a specific priority level assigned to both documents and reports, indicating a status of high importance within the library system. This designation is technically specified within the file's structure, appearing in the metadata, tags, and the dedicated priority field. When a document or report is designated as Core, it signals that the material holds elevated significance compared to standard entries. The classification ensures that these high-priority items are easily identifiable through their associated tags and metadata properties.

The application of the Core label is consistent across different types of records, whether categorized broadly as documents or specifically as reports. By marking these items with this priority level, the system emphasizes their critical nature. Consequently, the Core designation serves as a unified indicator of importance, relying on explicit fields and tags to maintain clarity regarding the asset's value within the broader library system infrastructure.</data>
